    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-23T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-23T13:00:00-05:00" n="1037"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1037">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">102.78/2–2346</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pawley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-23T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 23, 1946—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>211. For Wheeler and Hutson<note n="99" xml:id="d1037fn99">Leslie A. Wheeler,
                        Director, Foreign Agricultural Relations, and John B. Hutson, Commodity
                        Credit Corporation. Both of these agencies were parts of the Department of
                        Agriculture.</note> Agriculture from Haggerty.<note n="1" xml:id="d1037fn1"
                        >John J. Haggerty, Agricultural Attaché.</note> Have personally investigated
                    wheat situation and food supply in Peru. Mills closed and closing lack of wheat.
                    Stocks of flour including wheat on hand and afloat sufficient for requirements
                    through March. Shipment <pb facs="1285" n="1267" xml:id="pg_1267"/> of 8000 tons
                    from United States promised in telegram 147<note n="2" xml:id="d1037fn2">Not
                        printed.</note> will partly meet April requirements. Normal imports hand to
                    mouth basis 12,500 tons wheat monthly. Personally believe starvation and food
                    riots can be avoided with deliveries 8000 tons from all sources monthly be [<hi
                        rend="italic">by?</hi>] consuming existing rice stocks and current crop rice
                    and beans as available. Urge all possible consideration deliveries 8000 tons
                    monthly beginning with promised cargo March. Wheat preferable to flour since
                    bran and shorts important to milk supply. Also closing of mills will exaggerate
                    crisis in public mind with grave consequences in markets and to Govt. From
                    political standpoint suggest advisability supplying United States wheat now and
                    channelizing Argentine wheat as available into general channels.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Pawley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
